\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Jordà - 2005 - Estimation and Inference of Impulse Responses by Local Projections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Oscar Jorda (2005) introduces a new method for estimating impulse responses using local projections instead of the traditional Vector Autoregression (VAR) approach.
 The key motivation is that VAR models impose strong assumptions on the underlying data-generating process (DGP),
 which may not hold in pracrice.
 
\series bold
SUCH as what?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
The key points in the paper is:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
VARs assume that the observed variables follow a specific multivariate time series process
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Even if the macroeconomy can be described by a VAR,
 the subset of variables available to researches may follow a 
\series bold
VARMA
\series default
 model instead.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
VARs often require long lag lengths to approximate the true DGP correctly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
They can be significantly misspecified leading to biased or inconsistent IPR estimates.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Alternative approach –> Local Porjections
\series default
:
 Instead of estimating hte full dynamic system (like VAR),
 local projections estimate 
\series bold
separate regressions
\series default
 for each forecast horizon.
 And the advantages are:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Simpler estimation:
 Uses OLS and standrad regression software.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
More robust to misspecification.
 
\series bold
WHY IS THAT?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Allows for flexible and nonlinear specifiations,
 which VAR have trouble handling.
 
\series bold
WHY IS THAT,
 and why does LP allow for it?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Inference is simpler.
 Does not require asymtotic approximations like the deltage method.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Paragraph
1) What strong assumptions do VAR models impose on the DGP,
 which may not hold in practice?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
VAR models assume that the observed time series data fllow a specific multivariate linear proces:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=A_{1}Y_{t-1}+...+A_{p}Y_{t-p}+\varepsilon_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of endogenonus variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the coefficent matrice and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an error term assumed to be white noise.
 In realy these asumption often do not hold due to varies reasons such as.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
1) True DGP may follow a VARMA not a VAR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It has been shown that even if the macroeconomy is well cescribed by a VARMA model,
 researches typically approx it with a VAR.
 However a VAR cannot properly caputra the MA terms,
 leading to potential misspecification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
2) The VAR may require too many lags.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In practice adding to many lags reduce DOF,
 and increases estimation uncertainty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
3) Nonlinearities in the ecoconmy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Many economic relationships are not striclt linear,
 but a standard VAR is limited to caputring 
\series bold
only linear dependencies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For example,
 monetary policy effects may differ in recessions vs booms,
 but a linear VAR does not allows for this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
NK-DSGE model
\series default
 often generente nonlinear dynamics (Rotemberg pricing introduces quadratic cost function),
 which cannot be caputered by a standard VAR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
4) Incorrect identificatuion of shocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In standard VARs,
 structual shock are often indeified using 
\series bold
Cholesky decompision,

\series default
 which imposes a arbitrary ordering of variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This means that IR depnd on assumptions about the contemporaneous interactions,
 which may not reflect the true economic structure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
2) Why are LP more robust to misspecifition than VAR?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Key-reason LP does not assume a fixed multivariate structure but esitmates each IP step seperatly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
1) No reason to assume the entire DGP is correct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
VAR IR repend on the entire model being correctly specified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the lag length is too short,
 a VAR misses important dynamics,
 if it is too long the VAR wastes degree of freedom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
LP fixed this problem by estimating each horizon separately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This means error from one period do not carry over to another,
 avoiding compounding misspecification errors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
2) LP handle missing variables better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If some relevant variables are omitted,
 a VAR will spread the error across all IR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
LP estiamtes each horizon independently,
 meaning the misspecification only affect on regression at a time,
 reducing the overall bias.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
3) Why do VARs sruggle with nonlinearities,
 and why do LP´s allow for them?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
1) VAR models assume linear relationship.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A standard VAR assumes the relationsihp between bariables is constant over time,
 and can be represented as a lienar system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Howver in reality:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Economic effects can be asymmetric (raising interest rates might reduce inflation more than cutting rates increases it).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The effects of a shock might depend on the state of the economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Variables might interact in nonlinear ways.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Description
2) LP allows for nonlienar specification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since LP uses separate regressions for each forecast horizon,
 we can add nonlinear transformation (quadratic,
 cubic or interactions terms etc).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This allows LP to captura state-dependent effects,
 for instance difference responses in booms vs recessions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
LP can inorporta threshold effects,
 where the response changes depending on the level of another varaible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Impulse responses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a fundamental tool in macroeconometrics,
 and can help us understand how an economic variable reacts over time to a shock in another variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
1) What is an impulse reponse?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An IRF shows the effect of a one-time shock (impulse) to one variable on another variable in a system over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In mathematical terms,
 an IPR is the expected difference between two forecasts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
IR_{t}\left(t,s,d_{t}\right)=E\left[y_{t+s}\mid v=d_{i};X_{t}\right]-E\left[y_{t+s}\mid v=0;X_{t}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Where 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 is the endeongeous variable of interest at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the structural shock occuring at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $d_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the size and type of shock (e.g.
 a 1% monteray policy shock).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the information set available at time t.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Paragraph
2) What does this equation mean?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The IPR measures the difference between:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The expected path of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 if the economy recieve a shock a t
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The expected payh of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 if no shock occurs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimation and inference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jorda critiques the tradional approach to esitmaitng IPR using a Wold decomposition of a VAR model.
 He argues that this is only valid if the VAR model correctly represent the true GDP,
 which is often not the case.
 Insted he proposes that IPR can be defined independently of the DGP,
 making them more robust.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
1) Traditional Approach:
 Wold decomposition & VAR models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In time series econometrics,
 the 
\series bold
Wold 
\series default
decomposition theorem states that any covariance stationary time series,
 can be written as a moving average (MA) process of past shocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This means that any VAR(p) model can be rewritten as an infinite Vector Moving Average (VMA) representation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{t}=\sum_{j=0}^{∞}\Phi_{j}v_{i-j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 vector of ednougenous variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 vector of reduced from disturbances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{j}$
\end_inset

 are impulse response coefficent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
IPR in a VAR is then obtained by shocking 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 and using this VMA representation to compute the dynamic effects over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Why is this a problem?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The VAR models must be correctly specified.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If the estimated VAR model does not match the true GDP,
 the computed IPR will be baised.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Misspecification compouns errors over time.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Since IPR in a VAR are computed recursively,
 small specification errors get larger at longer horizons.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Paragraph
2) Alternative approach:
 Defining IPR without a DGP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jorda argues that IPR can be defined without assuming the correct DGP.
 He adopts a forecast-based approach,
 and defines IPR as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
IR_{t}\left(t,s,d_{t}\right)=E\left[y_{t+s}\mid v=d_{i};X_{t}\right]-E\left[y_{t+s}\mid v=0;X_{t}\right],s=0,1,2,...,
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $E[.]$
\end_inset

 denotes the best mean squared error predictors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 random vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $X\equiv\left(y_{t-1},y_{t-2},...\right)^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is past observartion of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 and represents the information available at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 vevtor of reduced form disturbances.
 The unexpected shocks driving fluctuations in the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix,
 whose columsn 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}$
\end_inset

 contain the relevant experimental shock.
 Helpts extract structua shocks from raw regressions residuals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Sidenote:

\series default
 Unstanding 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 in a VAR framefork.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Ub a VAR nidek we estunate the reduced from equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=A_{1}Y_{t-1}+...+A_{p}Y_{t-p}+v_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 vector of endogenous variable (e.g.
 GDP,
 Inflation,
 interest rates).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 vector of reduce dfrom distrubances (estimated residuals).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The var-cvar matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varSigma=E\left(v_{t}v_{t}^{\prime}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recover the structural breaks,
 from the reduced form residausl,
 we define:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=D\epsilon_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 vector of structural shocks (e.g.
 monetary policy shock).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is thet 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 trnasfomration matrix that maps reduced form erros to structural shocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Insering 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}=D\epsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}\varSigma= & E\left(D\epsilon_{t}\left(D\epsilon_{t}\right)^{\prime}\right)\\
= & DE\left(\epsilon_{t}\epsilon_{t}^{\prime}\right)D^{\prime}
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
By assumption the structures shocks 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
uncorrelated and have identivy variance,
 i.e.:
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\epsilon_{t}\epsilon_{t}^{\prime}\right)=I_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}\varSigma= & DI_{n}D^{\prime}\\
= & DD^{\prime}
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To recover the structural shocks frm the reduced form residuals,
 we need to invert this relationship.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varSigma$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and positive definite,
 is has a Cholesky decomposition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varSigma=PP^{\prime}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 i s a lower trianglur matrix.
 If we the n compare with the Cholesky decomposition we set:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
DD^{\prime}=PP^{\prime}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recover the structural shocks,
 we need to express them in terms of the reduced from errors:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon_{t}=D^{-1}v_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $DD^{\prime}=PP^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 such that:
 
\begin_inset Formula $D=P^{-1}$
\end_inset

,
 this allows us to write the relationship,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t}=P^{-1}v_{t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Intutition behind this approach:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the residuals from the reduced form VAR,
 i.e.
 the error that remain after estimating the var model.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
These residuals contain a mix of idfferent economic shocks,
 but we do not know their true sources.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
But to distinguish between strutucal shocks 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 and just random noice,
 we use a 
\series bold
Cholesky decompoistion.

\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Because the reduced from residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 are correlated,
 meaning they are influence by multiple shocks at the same time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Cholesky decompsition imposes a causal ordering that allows us to separate the structural shocks frmo the mixed residuals.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Where we use the relationship:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t}=D^{-1}v_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 determines the contemporianeous relationships between variables.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Paragraph
Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lets conside a VAR with two macroeconomic variables:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
GDP growth,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}^{GDP}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Interest rate 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}Î$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reduced from residuals,
 observered errors in the esitmated VAR are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{t}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
v_{t}^{GDP}\\
v_{t}^{i}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resuduals are a mixture of structural shock,
 which we assume to be the true econimic disturbances:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon_{t}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\epsilon_{t}^{GDP}\\
\epsilon_{t}^{i}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the fundamental relationship:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{t}=D\epsilon_{t}\Leftrightarrow
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
v_{t}^{GDP}\\
v_{t}^{i}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
d_{11} & d_{12}\\
d_{21} & d_{22}
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
\epsilon_{t}^{GDP}\\
\epsilon_{t}^{i}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $d_{11}$
\end_inset

 is the dirrect effecot of a GDP shock on GDP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $d_{12}$
\end_inset

 is the effect of a monteary policy shock to GDP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $d_{21}$
\end_inset

 is the effect of a GDP shock on montary policy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $d_{22}$
\end_inset

 is the effect of a policy shock on interest rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use Cholesky decomposition and assume GDP is more exogenous than intereset rates,
 we impose a triangular structure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
d_{11} & 0\\
d_{21} & d_{22}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
i.e.
 GDP only repsondes to its own shock,
 meaning nonetary policy does not have instnatenous effet on GDP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Structural identification remains an open probælem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In VAR models the contemporenous relationship between variables are not dirrectly opbservered.
 And as seen above,
 standard approaches,
 e.g.
 Cholesky decomposition impose assumptions to recover structual shocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Jorda does not focus on identification in his paper but instead introduces a flexible framefork where the experiment 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 (shock structure) is chosen without loss of genereality 
\series bold
WHAT DOES THIS MEAN?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
The goal of impulse responce estimation is to obtatin multi-stpe forecasts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Expression (1) shows that an impulse responce function (IRF) is calculated by compoaring two expected future paths.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Traditional VARs compute IRFs by recursively iterating on the estimated model.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This works well if the model is correctly specified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
However if the model is misspecified,
 impulse resopnses will be biased.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Instead of estimaitng a full model and recursively forecasting each step,
 we estimate separate regression for each horizon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
This is the core idea behind Local Projections.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Local projections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we consider estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 using past data 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y_{t-1},...,y_{t-p}\right)^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 ,
 specifically:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{t+s}=\alpha^{s}+B_{1}^{s+1}y_{t-1}+B_{2}^{s+1}y_{t-2}+...+B_{p}^{s+1}y_{t-p}+u_{t+s}^{s},s=0,1,2,...,h
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where we have that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t+s}$
\end_inset

:
 The future value in period 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 of the variable we want to estimate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{s}$
\end_inset

:
 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 vector of constant:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}^{s+1}$
\end_inset

 are matrices of coffeicients for each lag 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $s+1$
\end_inset

.
 I.e.
 describe the effect of past value on 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t+s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t+s}^{s}$
\end_inset

:
 The residuals (forecast errors),
 that captures everything not explained by past values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We denote the collection of (h) regressions in (2) as local projections.
 A term aptly evocative of nonparameteric considertions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jorda then define sthe IRF as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{IR}\left(t,s,d_{i}\right)=\hat{B}_{1}^{s}d_{i},s=0,1,2,...,h
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
I.e.
 the impulse response at horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is simply the estimated coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{1}^{s}$
\end_inset

 times the shock 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The normalization;
 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}^{0}=1$
\end_inset

,
 ust enstures that the shock starts at 0.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Consistency of the estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Referencing (Weiss,
 1991),
 saying that the multi-step forecast approach is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Consistent:

\series default
 As long as enough data is available.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Is asymtotically normal:
 
\series default
Meaning that estimates follow a nomrla distribution asymtotically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Why are the residuals uncorrelated with the regressors?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since the regressors are from 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $t-p$
\end_inset

,
 theyt are lagged vlaues.
 The forecast errors 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t+1}^{s}$
\end_inset

 only depend on the information from time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 onward.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This means the that OLS estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 are unbaised.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
VAR:

\series default
 Residuals may be correlated across equations,
 leading to potential bias if model is misspecified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
LP:

\series default
 Since each equation is estimated separately,
 this issue does not arise.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Practical Comments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
1) The maximum lag p,
 need not to be common to each horizon s.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In traditional VAR models,
 we typically select one lag length for the entire system,
 using information criteria.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In LP,
 the est choice of p may vary across forecast horisons s.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For short horizons we may need fewer lags becuase recent history is more relevant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For longer horizons we might need more lags to captura long-term effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
2) The lag length and the dimensions of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 ,
 will impose DoF constraints on the maximm practical horizon h,
 for very small samples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When estimating LPs,
 we need enough data to esitmate each horizon-specific regresions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we inclde to many lags,
 we lose DoF because each lag requires more parameters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
3) We can estimate impulse responses using separate univarite regressions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
VAR:

\series default
 all equations are estimated jointly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
LP:

\series default
 We do not need to estimate all regressions togheter,
 and can just estimate one at a time using simple univariate regressiosn.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
LP are useful in computing hte forecast-error variance decomposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\series bold
Sidenote 
\series default
Forecast-Error Variance Decompisition (FEVD):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Measures how much the forecast error in a variable is explained by each struturcal shock over idfferent forecast horizons.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It thus tells us which shocks drive fluctuations in a variable over time.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
How much of GDP´s variation is explained y monetary policy shocks?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Description
Forecast-error definition in LP:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The forecat error can be derived directly from eq.
 2,
 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{t+s}-E\left(y_{t+s}\mid X_{t}\right)=u_{t+s}^{s},s=0,1,2,...
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus the MSE of the forecast is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{alignedat}{1}MSE_{u}= & E\left[\left(y_{t+s}-E\left[y_{t+s}\mid X_{t}\right]\right)\left(y_{t+s}-E\left[y_{t+s}\mid X_{t}\right]\right)^{\prime}\right]\\
= & E\left[u_{t+s}^{s}\left(u_{t+s}^{s}\right)^{\prime}\right]
\end{alignedat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The forecsat error is just the variance of the residuals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Forecast-error-Variance decomposed into structural shocks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now Jorda decompose the forecast error variance into contributions from differenct structural shocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step.1) Transform the forecast error variance using D:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Jorda applies the transformation matrix D,
 (which realtes to the reduced form residuals to structural shocks 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MSE=D^{-1}E\left[u_{t+s}^{s}\left(u_{t+s}^{s}\right)^{\prime}\right]\left(D^{-1}\right)^{\prime}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
MSE is now normalized into a form where it can be directly decomposed into strucural shocks.
 
\series bold
HOW DOES THIS relatate to Cholesky Decomposition?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How does this differ from tradiational VAR FEVD?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In traditional VAR models,
 the variance decomposition is derived from the moving average (MA) representation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MSE_{u}=E\left(u_{t+s}\left(u_{t+s}\right)^{\prime}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Which is computed recursively using VAR Impulse response coefficents:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MSE_{U}=\sum_{i=0}^{s}\Phi_{i}E\left[u_{t}u_{t}^{\prime}\right]\Phi_{i}^{\prime}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the MA coefficients,
 derived from inverting the VAR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(u_{t}u_{t}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the residual variance-covariance matrix of the VAR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why does this matter?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
VAR:

\series default
 The accuracy of the variance decomposition depends on how well 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 approximate the true GDP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
LP:

\series default
 we estimate the variance decomposition directly from the regression residuals,
 without needing to assume a dynamic structure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Relation to VAR and inference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both LP and traditional VARs aim to estimate IPR,
 but do so in differnet ways
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Traditional VAR approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A VAR(p) model for a vector of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 looks like:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{t}=\mu+\Pi^{\prime}X_{t}+v_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is an i.i.d vector of disturbances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 matrix of consts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}=\left(y_{t-1},...,y_{t-p}\right)^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $np\times1$
\end_inset

 stacked vector of past values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi=\left[\Pi_{1},...,\Pi_{p}\right]$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times np$
\end_inset

 coefficent matrix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can thet nrewrite this VAR(p) into the companion form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{t}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
y_{t}-\mu\\
y_{t-1}-\mu\\
...\\
y_{t-p+1}-\mu
\end{array}\right],F\equiv\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
\Pi_{1} & \Pi_{2} & ... & \Pi_{p-1} & \Pi_{p}\\
I & 0 & ... & 0 & 0\\
0 & I & ... & 0 & 0\\
\dots & \dots & \dots & \dots & 0\\
0 & 0 & ... & I & 0
\end{array}\right];v_{t}\equiv\left[\begin{array}{c}
v_{t}\\
0\\
...\\
0
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Where:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the state vector,
 that allows us to write the VAR(p) system af as single first-order equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the companion matrix,
 where the first row contains the VAR coefficeints,
 and the identify matrices (I).
 Its thus determines how shocks propagate over time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the shocks,
 and rhte first block contains the original shocks 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Accoridng to (5) and (6),
 we can write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{t}=FW_{t-1}+v_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Where we compute s-step ahead forecast,
 since,
 we can just iterate forward,
 i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}W_{t}= & FW_{t-1}+v_{t}\\
W_{t}= & F\left(FW_{t-2}+v_{t-1}\right)+v_{t}=Fv_{t-1}+F^{2}W_{t-2}+v_{t}\\
W_{t}= & Fv_{t-1}+F^{2}\left(FW_{t-3}+v_{t-2}\right)+v_{t}\\
W_{t}= & v_{t}+Fv_{t-1}+Fv_{t-2}+F^{3}W_{t-3}\\
= & ...\\
W_{t+s}= & v_{t+s}+Fv_{t+s-1}+...+F^{s}v_{t}+F^{s+1}W_{t-1}
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the first row of 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}$
\end_inset

 matrix,
 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 then if we want to extract 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{t+s}-\mu=v_{t+s}+F_{1}^{1}v_{t+s-1}+...+F_{1}^{s}v_{t}+F_{1}^{s+1}\left(y_{t-1}-\mu\right)+F_{p}^{s+1}\left(y_{t-p}-\mu\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

,
 upper 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 block of thet matric 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{s}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 raised to the power s).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus we have that:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 represents the mediate shock at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Past shocks,
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t+s-1},...,v_{t}$
\end_inset

 also contribute to 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 and their effect is controlled by 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}^{s}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is the first row block of 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{s}$
\end_inset

 ,
 and determines how each past shock propagates over time .
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
If we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}$
\end_inset

 is covariance-stationary (i.e.
 the eigenvalues of F lie inside the unit circle),
 the initie Vector moving average representation of the original VAR in expression (5) is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{t}=\gamma+v_{t}+F_{1}^{1}v_{t-1}+F_{1}^{2}v_{t-2}+...+F_{1}^{s}v_{t-s}+...
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and impulse response funtction is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
IR\left(t,s,d_{i}\right)=F_{1}^{s}d_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Connecting VAR-based impulse responses and LP impulse responses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jorda establishes this relationship.
 First,
 Local projection IPR (from earlier) is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{t+s}=\alpha^{1}+B_{1}^{s+1}y_{t-1}+B_{2}^{s+1}y_{t-2}+...+B_{p}^{s+1}y_{t-p}+u_{t+s}^{s}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we now compare VAR IPR,
 rewritten:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{t+s}=\left(I-F_{1}^{s}-...-F_{p}^{s}\right)\mu+F_{1}^{s+1}y_{t-1}+...+F_{p}^{s+1}y_{t-p}+\left(v_{t+s}+F_{1}^{1}v_{s-1}+...+F_{1}^{s}v_{t}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Here we can quite netly observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\alpha^{s}=\left(I-F_{1}^{s}-...-F_{p}^{s}\right)\mu\\
B_{1}^{s+1}=F_{1}^{s+1}\\
u_{t+s}^{s}=\left(v_{t+s}+F_{1}^{1}v_{t+s-1}+...+F_{1}^{s}v_{t}\right)
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Hence,
 when the DGP is the VAR in (5),
 expression (10) and (11),
 estblish the equaivlence between impulse responses calculated by local projections and with this VAR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the true DGP is a var,
 then LP recover the same IPR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Ecpression (12) shows that the error terms of the local projection 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t+s}^{s}$
\end_inset

,
 are a moving average of the forecast errors from time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $t+s$
\end_inset

 ,
 which can be used to improve efficiency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Estimation of local projections and link to VAR structure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the true DGP is a var,
 alle these separate LP equation are linked through their residual structure.
 Thus we can stack all horizons into a single system and esitmate it jointly using GLS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Stacking the h-step ahead local projection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simplicy notation define:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}=\left(v_{t+1},v_{t+2},...,v_{t+h}\right)^{\prime}$
\end_inset

,
 which stacks the forecast errors for each horizon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}=\left(y_{t-1},y_{t-2},...,y_{t-p}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which is thte matrix of ressors (pst value of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now rewrite the entire system of h LPs as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=X_{t}\Psi+V_{t}\Phi
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where (ignoring the constant term) the parmeters matrices are constrained as follows:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the stacked vector of all horizons 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t+s}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 contains the lagged values of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 is the matrix of coefficients that determine how past value influecnce future values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the stacked forecast erros.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

;
 A transformation matrix that links errors across horizons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we just estimate one large system of equations.
 And we got htat:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
F_{1}^{1} & F_{1}^{2} & ... & F_{1}^{h}\\
F_{2}^{1} & F_{2}^{2} & ... & F_{1}^{h-1}\\
... & ... & ... & ...\\
F_{p}^{1} & F_{p}^{2} & ... & F_{p}^{h}
\end{array}\right],\Phi=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
I_{n} & F_{1}^{1} & ... & F_{1}^{h}\\
0 & I_{n} & ... & F_{1}^{h-1}\\
\dots & \dots & \dots & \dots\\
0 & 0 & ... & I_{n}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

:
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}^{s}$
\end_inset

 represent the effect of past values 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t-1}$
\end_inset

 on the future values.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi:$
\end_inset

 Ensures that residuals at different gorizons remain connected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we thne define the variance-covariance matrix of residuals:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(v_{t}v_{t}^{\prime}\right)=\Sigma_{v}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since we stacked the Local Projections,
 the variance of the entire system follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(V_{t}V_{t}^{\prime}\right)=\left(I_{h}\varotimes\Sigma_{v}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $I_{h}$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix of size h,
 which account for the different forecast horizons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\varotimes$
\end_inset

 denotes the 
\series bold
Kronecker product
\series default
,
 (All elements in A is multiplied with B).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Jorda & Taylor 2024
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ting jeg skal forstå:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
VAR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Wold decomposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
covariance stationary time series,
 can be written as a moving average (MA) process of past shocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Endogenitetsproblem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
LP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
VAR vs LP:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bias/Variance tradeoff
\end_layout

